data.jamchartnote: This version contains a stripped down intro, an uncharacteristic guitar solo and the first known recording of an adlibbed Ambrose rap.
Great high energy Head On/Pill leading into a brief drum segment into an ambient jam with Stu flute playing taking center stage, brought back into high energy Pill.
This version features an iconic moment where Stu realizes he can sing through his pickups, as well as potentially the first "Am I In Heaven?" quotes in Head On/Pill.
High energy and containing amazing vocals from Ambrose and crazy drumming.
An older Gizz jam containing high energy snippets in and out of the Pill segment of Head On/Pill and Am I In Heaven?, along with plenty of Cellophane and Hot Water teases and electric jamming.

After a high energy performance of the song, the band quiets down after a few fans are kicked out for crowd surfing. Stopping the music, Stu demands to speak to someone about it and asks to bring them back in.
The band’s tuning turns into a 14 minute jam to start the show
Super stellar playing throughout with heavy vocoder usage.
Adam Halliwell (of Mildlife)'s beautiful flute playing adds another layer of sound to this already amazing tease and quote filled Head On/Pill.
The band prepares for a heavy performance of "Murder of the Universe" only to have technical difficulties with Han-Tyumi, leading to a shortened instrumental performance.
A notably long "Head On/Pill" with a heavy emphasis on Ambrose's harmonica throughout.
Following Cyboogie and Acarine, this version starts pretty normal and they let it ride as they tend to do, but then the vocoder comes back out. Sounds like Cyboogie and Sense had a baby.
Fantastic playing throughout and heavy synth climaxing in deep vocoder usage from Joey results in a particularly heavy and "evil" version.
Guitar-focused but with a steady drumbeat anchor, accented with Amby's floaty synth work in particular. Joey in fine form, leading mostly. Not yet the full band improv of 2023 Senses

Living up to the song’s name, the band drifts gently into a truly spellbinding jam, moving through some gorgeous guitar melodies which then comes down to staccato intertwining interplay. The guitars then open up into some resplendent and contemplative ambiance before slowly and patiently returning to the song. However it is truly the synths that are the star of the show, holding everything together aloft on a warm glowing cloud, guiding the band in serenity from beginning to end.
This energetic version features Ambrose crowd surfing after a soulful "Bitter" call and response. Howlin' Wolf's Back Door Man and Cut Throat Boogie playfulness add to this 11.5 minute boogie.
Features Stu on flute with a typical Pill flute jam, but also contains a rare Hot Water jam with flute.

The first 15 minutes was a more standard Head On/Pill medley and contained many teases, but the last 15 minutes was a big jam featuring ORB and Stonefield. It was featured in "A Brief History of Planet Earth" on Chunky Shrapnel.

This show opening, first acoustic, first post-covid version of The River is a major indication of the direction the band was moving in at the time. Unlike any previous version, the first jam section showcases a looser, inspired and creatively liberated band, as it opens up into fun interplay between all members of the band before simmering down to a whisper. The outro jam features strong playing from all and great variations on the composed outro licks with a particularly jazzy flair.

After starting off in a typically strong manner, the band briefly moves through a rather unique major key jam before returning to the normal mood of the jam. Much like the rest of the show, everyone is listening to each other with intent and improvising with precision to great result.

The first acoustic rendition of Her and I is quite strong, as the jam moves into a rather dark and jazzy jam, with great piano contributions from Ambrose. The band explores this moody space for a few minutes before returning to the song via a rambunctious harmonica solo. The end moves back into that darker mode, before building back up as Stu repeatedly says “Bye bye” to the crowd while simultaneously being unable to stop jamming. A appropriate closer to a fantastic and groundbreaking show.

The main jam segment is exceptional on all fronts, from Amby’s deft piano and harmonica playing, to the focused guitar work from Stu, Joey, and Cook exploring multiple themes, to the rhythm section’s pocketed groove. The rest of the song is also quite strong; every section is performed with gusto, from the first section’s great banter and interplay, to the third section’s deliberate fade, to the outro’s swagger of a band at its prime. A definite contender for the title of GOAT River.

Still in its infancy, this "Tap" bears witness to an inspired Stu dueting on flute with Cecil Coleman (Body Type) for a little "flute jam." Some nice harmonic interplay and Am I In Heaven?-style vamping ensues before a bevy of proper teases and quotes in the customary energetic run up to the coda.
Only Acoustic Version
The first time they really jammed out on this song.
Longest live version of this track to date.

A super punchy and energetic version. Having achieved its now-trademark blistering speed, they further push the boundaries of the budding jam vehicle and take an offramp to (a then-unknown) Hell's Itch jam. A vocally inspired "drip drip" section gives way to the hottest "Tap" peak yet. Cavs is on fire!

Does “biggest show gap in years” count?

Crumbling Castle had been played literally every couple shows for years. Then the band took a little break from playing it; this is its triumphant return (after Covid paused live music), as the encore for a tiny punk venue in northern California.  (2nd Biggest gap for CC, after 2017-11-18)
A near 5 minutes jam between Mr. Beat->Sea of Trees sets up a 10+ minute fully jammed out version of this song, one of the oldest in their discography.
After the first section, Stu announces, "Alright, now let’s do this extra fast", prompting Joey and Ambrose to yell "Fuck everything", launching into a super fast and high energy River.
This supersized version has lots of quality guitar noodling to extend its length, snappy Cavs, a thrilling "drip drip" stop-start crescendo, and most notably, an Iron Lung jam section
Primarily an instrumental, with only 2 sets of lyrics being sung, this 10 minute chill low energy jam contains alternate lyrics and slowed teases of The Dripping Tap and Head On/PIll.

Coming in from Sea of Trees, it seems like just a tease of Hot Water followed by a tease of Shanghai, but Ambrose's chants of "Hot Water" turn it into a chilled jam, that increases in energy halfway though, like a pot of boiling… hot water.

Beginning with a peaceful calm typical of the song, the band moves toward an evil jam which will become typical in future FAFYLs. They methodically open a portal leading to a relentless and pummeling descent into hell filled with tight, crunchy and melodic metal guitars, apocalyptic synthwork, and raging harmonica. After about five minutes of face melting delirium, the band suddenly falls away back into the original mellow groove, all the while incorporating and playing with themes from the metal section.
Spanning 20+ minutes, it contains an extended intro, killer lengthy harmonica jamming from Ambrose, sax jamming and amazing vocal work from Ambrose as well, along with a high energy ending.
Ethereal and soaring. The band pulls out the wings and flies through some thrilling and melodious passages including some pristine Pill teasing, making for a truly stellar rendition.
Super chill funky version starting off with a drum machine jam by Joey and ending in a guitar solo.
Very spacey and lengthy river with jazz elements.
Funky guitar playing, lengthy solo with vocals overlapping.
Only a partial video available, but worth watching for both a Dripping Tap jam and a Hypertension jam inside, both with lyrics, as well as Alter Me and Crumbling Castle high energy teases and quotes.

A more melodious jam than the Best Kept Secret “Tap” accompanies Stu’s (now customary?) Lake Perris plunge. Amby rips some harmonica, improvises some lyrics, and then implores the crowd: “Can we have our singer back on the stage?” It would be a mistake to dismiss this fun, funny, and creative version as a mere retread!

Highly improvisational and groovy, the jam starts out with percussive guitar work which morphs into some Ice V teasing and Iron Lung quotes. The jam moves into a psychedelic fury which quickly chills out and gets real spacey as Stu picks up the flute. Building up from a guitar, drums and flute trio, a heavy rocking and fast paced jam emerges, which simply rages. After a few minutes, Cavs shifts to a half time beat which transitions smoothly back into the song. “Well that took an unexpected turn” says Joey.

A bloodcurdling scream, a hypertensive first jam, a hellish itch, and a Pill to cure all ills; this show-closing jam vessel travels far and wide with its bodily imagery. The Gizzy Boys’ rhythm section lock a tight grip on “drip drip” while Stu, Amby, and Joey rip (especially during the coda jam, holy “Tap”)!
The Evil River
Ambrose and Joey provides scat vocals to the song's jazzy intro before heading into a dynamic seventeen minute rendition.
This version conjures up the "Hypertension" segment of "The Land Before Timeland" for an ominous interlude.

The band slithers towards a Hypertension jam that transforms into Altered Beast, then emerges with a clear Hypertension tease. After Invisible Face, they boom back into EDR to a raucous close complete with spooky background vocals.

The third of three monstrous October renditions sees the band grooving through Ice V teasing, before moving onto mystical and atmospheric passages, including a great breakdown jam at the 10 minute mark. The keys shine particularly bright in the back half of the jam. The band builds the energy back up to briefly return for a final refrain, before floating back to outer space for a little Magenta Mountain jam to close out.
Though not its usual immaculate, tight self, the Asheville “Tap” finds the band stretching out into new territory and mapping out “The Land Before Timeland”.
A calm start leads into a diabolical jam much heavier than other 2022 performance. After slowing into another calm chorus, the band speeds up before Ambrose kicks it into high gear.

Lucas makes a rare assertive appearance in the second jam of this festival “Tap,” and Stu follows suit leading the band in a brief excursion into minor-key jamming that ultimately culminates in a neat “Hypertension” section, which spans both D minor and major as they work back to “drip drip.”
Top tier version containing a Hells Bells intro jam.
Big jam that turns Evil and segues into Self-Immolate

This mashup of early gizz jams flows between Head On/Pill and Sea of Trees. It also contained improvized lyrics about animals in australia, and plenty of teases such as The Dripping Tap, Ice V, and Shanghai (with jam).
Spanning almost 15 minutes, this high energy rendition takes a brief but exciting detour into a metal-esque jam.

A behemoth of a version finds itself placed in the middle of one of the most playful sets the band has ever performed. From the get go the band is tight and energized featuring communicative interplay from all members. After moving through the composed section with aplomb, the main jam segment progresses in a manner similar to many electric renditions, ebbing and flowing through many ideas and themes, before cooling down and segueing into Wah Wah.

As the band moves into Wah Wah, Stu, Joey, and Amby take a moment to extemporize about the band’s ability to chill hard, and Stu’s inability to chill. Unlike most versions of Wah Wah, this rendition serves as a nice breather before segueing back into The River.

Upon returning to The River, the band speeds up and moves through an ominous passage before everyone drops out other than Joey. Stu comes in with an anthemic progression to which Cavs and Amby contribute nicely. This resolves into the third section, the ending of which features some nice Wah Wah teasing from Joey and a dramatic transition into the outro. A groovy and funky rendition of the outro provides a nice capper to a rendition of the River of epic proportions.
This energetic acoustic version has high energy chants of "should never be displayed" from Ambrose, and ends in a partial cover of Praise You by Fatboy Slim.
This 12 minute long version is played electric, instead of the acoustic version. It features a slowed down version of Iron Lung and a mashup of Straws in the Wind and Sense lyrics.

Spanning 15 minutes, with a great segue out of Lord of Lightning and features snippets of other songs. It starts off strong, then fades into a short Dripping Tap segment for about 3 minutes, before going into 2 minutes of Hot Water, then finishing off into Shanghai (including the extended jam) played on guitar, before transitioning into Big Fig Wasp.
On-point vocals and Cavs drumming like a man possessed lead into a heavy and powerful finish to the closer of the early set.
Referred to by fans as the ‘Dead River’
A long and winding "Shanghai" with Stu playing electric guitar throughout. His additions include funky, syncopated rhythms and a full solo during the song's peak.

An atypical and jammy intro sees Ambrose wander into the crowd, from where he eventually begins the song. Following the first chorus, a lengthy minor key jam emerges that grows increasingly tense and dark. Quotes and teases of Crumbling Castle and Cellophane build up to an intense peak. Returning back to the second jam section, the band weaves Head On/Pill into a jam reminiscent of the Dead-inspired progressions that popped up throughout the summer. The longest version to date, and worth every minute.
Sick segues on either end, this jam from the tour-opener is unleashed energy that crackles and sparks. Joey and Stu generate enough electricity to power this to the charts.
Longest ever Sleep Drifter with extensive teasing in the intro and a big jam into Honey.

Eschewing Joey’s traditional solo, the band instead opts for a funky and propulsive jam. Over this, solos emerge that evoke the freewheeling jazz fusion of early 70s Zappa and the Allmans. As the band returns to the typical outro progression, through maintaining the jam's unusual feel, Joey takes another raging solo to cap off a fiery and groundbreaking version.

A titanic and highly improvisational rendition in three movements. Spellbinding and focused, the band builds up the energy with some Converge teasing, before landing in a Mind Left Body-esque progression with great full band interplay. Returning to the traditional breakdown section, Stu does some incredible work, playing gorgeously melancholic melodies delicately, before building the energy up to close out the song. A must listen for any fan worth their salt.
Oscar Karls of Viagra Boys on saxophone.
Oscar Karls of Viagra Boys on saxophone.

Coming out of Hypertension and landing halfway through a great sequence of segues, the second jam is where the magic happens. Landing on the wrong key, an atypical jam emerges from the breakdown, with the band modulating back and forth between the key the band landed in and the song's original key to great effect. Following the final verse, they break it down with some Her and I and Presumptuous teases, before executing great segue into Presumptuous.
data.venuename: Plaza Mayor de El Poble Espanyol

data.jamchartnote: In an exemplary version highlighting the band’s improvisational chops on synths, the band rockets to outer space. They tack on a jam to the conclusion of the song propper, grooving out in a dancy, jazzy mood for a delightful five minutes.
data.venuename: Plaza Mayor de El Poble Espanyol

data.jamchartnote: An extended intro and an unusual mid song jam make this rendition well worth listening to. During the breakdown, a melancholic guitar duet emerges, which evolves into a raucous jam with some great harmonica work. The band sticks the landing back into the song proper before moving into Mr. Beat.
Ambrose lets loose with extended Torture Chamber lyrics and freestyles. Stu supports with "The Shrimp Reaper" vocals. This version also includes Stu giving extra attention to the flute.
Includes Unique 5/4 jam

After a smooth transition out of Ice V, Amby’s harmonica wail throws us into the Cut Throat Boogie. The band plays the first couple of verses straight, which is a stomping good time as always, but the real kicker is the appended blues jam. Amby once again takes the lead with a killer harmonica solo, before the band starts dishing out a dynamic plethora of teases of Flight b741 material, including repeated Sad Pilot riffs, as well as the never-before heard Rats in the Sky, Raw Feel and Field of Vision.
Unusually long version with a medley of teases
extensive improv and Ambrose antics

Opening a set in Berlin, the band starts with an unfamiliar setup of a large synth setup in the middle of the stage. Their playing slowly lets it become more and more obvious what they're going to debut, with low synths and samples strewn of Stu singing strewn throughout. It quickly blossoms into an excellent (and the first!) version of Extinction in a live setting, with yet more samples and synths not seen in Studio. It then slows into the bassline of Gondii, kicking off a two-in-one synth debut special.

A masterclass in teasing and a very classically gizz approach to The Dripping Tap. A blissful jam opens up after the second chorus, with Antarctica teases and quotes driving the jam towards a rewarding peak. One of the greatest ways to open a tour.

Cuts off after verse 1 and a slow-building blues jam reminiscent of Daily Blues starts. Eventually changes to a regular Gizz rock jam, then starts alternating quickly between blues jam and rock jam, amping up and culminating in some metal flourishes. After a few more quick and somewhat awkward alternations and a false ending, the jam ends, leaving the song unfinished.

The drum solo and bass accompaniment from Joey quickly break from norms. This drum solo is soon transformed into a haunting and spacey jam that builds steadily towards the outro and an epic close to the show.
slick Daily Bues -> Cut Throat, sick segue into Gamma
intro jam

Performing the first verse from an inflatable gator raft held up by the crowd, Ambrose delivers impassioned vocals throughout the song. Colorful guitar work winds into Billabong’s iconic slow-down section where, after Stu takes a quick restroom break, the band stick the landing. The first of the “Amby wander” Billabong Valley’s that became a definitive staple of the 2024 NA tour.

data.footnote: With Timmy; Dedicated to his friend Joey
data.jamchartnote: The band was joined on stage by audience member Timmy, who played Joey's part on the song. The emotional rendition of the song was dedicated to Timmy's late friend Joey.

A confident and ripping performance of Magma. Tight and creative jams that highlight the bands guitar work are matched with some of Ambrose’s more inspired saxophone playing. The end is taken to unusual lengths as the band cools the signature double time jam down before launching into the one of the heaviest outros Magma has ever seen.
River intro and jam
Ice V and WTT
motor spirit and dragon
Early rendition of the song featuring heavy trance feel followed by a strong build up to the climax.

A long and wild jam highlights one of Stu’s now signature crowd-surfing river dips. Alternate Antarctica lyrics from Amby and a plethora of teases - notably 46 & 2 (Tool) for a large duration - soundtrack Stu’s departure and return. A closing Tap to end all closer Taps.
killer jam, variety of teases
river motor spirit and tsc jams, various quotes
medieval synthy jams
first time played not following Robot Stop, contained RS outro as intro
Iron Vultures part 1
Iron Vultures part 2
disco outro, lsd river
daft punk-y/funky/bisco-y/prince-y

Transitioned out of Extinction, the band drifts from the song’s electronic DNA making way for an electric rendition that prominently features guitar. The song’s bright synths lead to delicate guitar lines before a commanding jam climbs to an overdrive soaked crescendo.
Jay Weinberg joined the band on drums for an energetic version of the song.

Cuts off after verse 1 and goes to a creative blues jam, similar to 8/15, but a bit more jammy and explorative and less straightforward. They jam and quote Gila Monster and eventually Mars For the Rich. The jam quiets down and leads to a full stop, then they finish the song post-jam.
data.venuename: Huntington Bank Pavilion at Northerly Island

data.jamchartnote: added to setlist during show, Amby on Sax, various teasing/quoting/jamming
data.venuename: Huntington Bank Pavilion at Northerly Island

Maniacal Cavs
Technical difficulties lead into an improvised jam instead of a traditional Magenta Mountain
Historical bustout, lyric changes, instrument changes
data.songname: God Is Calling Me Back Home

data.jamchartnote: Transitioned into from Sad Pilot with a Rats in the Sky intro, this Magma is a bit heavier and messier than its counterparts from summer ‘24. A standout performance from Cavs particularly as his drumming steers the band heavier and heavier. The outro is taken to its usual heights, but as it falls out the band changes key to E and transitions smoothly into Rats in the Sky.
vibey jammy ambient lofi
rhythmic synths
Funky set
elbow got a little jammy
river got a relallyy spacey part 2 and a high energy part 4
Jay Weinberg on drums for his birthday, Cavs strolls through crowd, Audience member Devin performs "Let's Ride" vocal
Jay Weinberg on drums for his birthday
heaven got that almost metal-y jam -> calm space -> mind fuzz part
Stu said it was filthier than usual
driving and high energy
high energy jam
New sections
jammy intro and partially acoustic
they jammed Dirt?!? also Joey on acoustic
lots of jamming, quotes, and teases

A blisteringly fast and wet The Dripping Tap. An intense rain storm rolled in shortly before the band took the stage, concerning Ambrose in particular as he voiced his fear for his life throughout the performance. Out of the second chorus a familiar, yet faster than usual, jam emerges. The band wastes little time re-entering the song proper with a frenetic and energetic finish. Following the song, the show was halted for 22 minutes due to torrential downpour.
delayed vocal sampling, free & confident guitar + synth jam
Stu on acoustic
face melting

A stylish intro kicks off a funkier than usual Magma. A tight first verse and jam give way to playful springy flourishes in the bridge. An energetic and powerful second jam that strays from the usual course of Magma follows, with creative guitar lines from Stu and Joey dominating before settling back into the verse. The outro is taken to a familiar double time intensity, but again, unique guitar work from Stu and Joey lend it a distinct character and sound.
killer transition, blend of instruments
impromptu and incomplete acapella rendition during barrier issue
Opened with a Sense-like intro and settled into a blissed-out, psychedelic jam with an Am I In Heaven? tease. Crumbling Castle teases and the surrounding jamming adds a hint of unease; -> This Thing.
Features an extended, Tool-like intro jam and a drum solo with heavy riffs it before launching into the song proper.

Acoustic. Riding a steady disco drumbeat throughout, opening with extended banter where the band lists off their crew. Unlike the heavy vibe of traditional Magmas, it flows into a lighter, psychedelic Silver Cord jam with lyrics.
data.venuename: The Rady Shell at Jacobs Park

data.jamchartnote: Acoustic. Despite only being Part I, it calmly stretches past 10 minutes. Contains in Motor Spirit and Theia teases before settling into a The Silver Cord vocal jam, with Theia quotes throughout.
data.venuename: The Rady Shell at Jacobs Park

data.jamchartnote: A fiery rendition with multiple teases
Gorgeous jam and outro
jammed they intro quite a bit, great intro
Amby gone wild feat a lengthier jam with heavy guitar interplay
chill intro jam with teases, pretty ambient jam before finishing
banger

Fantastic composed section that flows into a "Theia" vocal sample jam, followed by a synth pattern that almost feels like percussion layered over Cavs' drumming into the "Motor Spirit" callback, leading into another percussive synth section with robotic bleep-like noises, crashing into a high-energy finale before calming down -> The Silver Cord.

Transitioning from Theia, this rendition settles into an intro jam with Stu singing "The Silver Cord" through a vocoder, accompanied by orchestral samples. This leads into an ethereal composed section, followed by a darker, more intense passage with vocal samples layered over strong drumbeats from Cavs. The music then shifts into an entirely different sound that feels like alien dance music, with static-like synths at moments, ending in an ambient section where percussive drumming fades into Set.

-> The Silver Cord, the bassline fades in alongside chipmunk-like vocal samples. The bass fades out, then returns with a strong drop into the composed section featuring a disco drumbeat. After a fiery composed part, with Ambrose adding quotes from Pump Up the Jam, they build to a huge drop followed by various synth textures. Joey then switches to guitar, Lucas on bass, and the funk kicks in. They then ease into an ambient funk section with bass bombs from Lucas, before one last drop and -> Chang'e.
rave set
rave set
rave set
rave set
slot machine sampling (“better luck next time”)
joey on guitar for the entire song due to his synth breakin
serious Joey guitar soloing atypical of Gizz’s repetitive solo style
New intro; extended jam prior to final verse
boogie jam not unlike those of Aug/Sep tour. Pretty long and wide reaching too.
atypical outro jam
Instrumentation, Spectrum jam, etc
Intense, firey & psychedelic.
dark star style jam in the middle
Jammed out like never before
Elaborate intro with multiple unique jams.

data.footnote: Debut; with King Stingray and Stuart Kellaway
data.jamchartnote: Similar in groove and funkiness to the recent Set synth table jams, the band is joined by opening act King Stingray to perform a funky cover of the Yothu Yindi song about Indigenous Australian’s campaign for recognition as traditional owners of the land, accompanied by founding bass guitarist Stuart Kellaway
Featuring an extended jam, this one had some extra mustard on it
Might be the most lowkey electric performance of it ever with an entire Iron Lung jam and a bluesy disco section
Full on metal jam at the end with Grim Reaper jam
An unusually long rendition featuring an extended jam section which contained Daily Blues quotes, Block of Ice (Osees) teases, and a small dash of “evil”.
Featured early and often Hypertension teases, extensive jamming, and weaving in between both songs.
A nearly 23 minute version featuring chill jamming and a variety of teases.

The longest version by a full 8 minutes, this Gilgamesh featured jamming throughout. The intro and outro were both extended, there was a layered ethereal section, and Magenta Mountain was teased and quoted.
data.venuename: Plaza Mayor de El Poble Espanyol

data.jamchartnote: The longest to date version. Featured major key synthy jams.
data.venuename: Plaza Mayor de El Poble Espanyol

data.jamchartnote: This Magenta Mountain expertly toed the line between synthy jam and high energy rager. It featured a metronome click and a transition into The Grim Reaper.
data.venuename: Plaza Mayor de El Poble Espanyol

data.jamchartnote: Longest version to date.  Features an extended jam with multiple teases and Terrapin-esque undertones.
This was the debut of the synth table version of Slow Jam 1. It also featured Ambrose on saxophone.
This version features a mid-improvisation transition into a cover of Jailbreak (AC/DC)

data.footnote: With fan Ignas on Stu’s guitar
data.jamchartnote: Dragon featured a fan named Ignas on Stu’s Holy Explorer guitar. The band invited him on stage after seeing his sign with a request to play Dragon. He notably crushed the particularly difficult guitar part.
An uptempo and “evil” version featuring unknown quotes from Ambrose.
An excellent version with a lava-esque intro and Phantom Island quotes.
Another rock version of the song, but this time featuring  a The Land Before Timeland jam and Iron Lung teases and quotes.
A rendition including a metal section and whammy from Stu, as well as the origin story for the music video.
Featuring alternate lyrics and a spacy Dripping Tap/Hot Water Jam.
Unusual "grimy" outro leading into Venusian 2

Hot Water is preceded by an ethereal jam section while The Orchestra of St. Luke's takes a set break which seamlessly leads into a driving intro to the song. The song itself also features extended jamming throughout, including a driving and heavier than usual section.

-> from Set, this Extinction weaves its way through multiple sections of frenetic, glitchy beats. An energetic first two verses leads to a meditative section where Cavs backs off. Gorgeous synth work from Joey and Cookie picks the energy back up before a driving jam emerges and takes the performance to a close.

After the Chicago Philharmonic left the stage following Grow Wings and Fly (which itself contained a Theia jam), the band meandered into a rock-arrangement Theia. Eventually it launches into some up tempo teases and jamming before settling back into a tasty groove before starting up a Field of Vision jam with some ZZ Top teasing.
The second edition of Kepler on Nathan, this rendition has a strong groove throughout and featured some hard drops.
Gaia features a Cavs drum solo during which the audience participates with some chants, followed by a medly of AIIH and Magma teases.
A pretty unique performance featuring Jello Biafra of the Dead Kennedys on vocals. Before the song the band talks about being inspired by their work.
This bustout is the largest known show gap and features Stu on flute with an extended outro.

This Magenta Mountain continues the trend of magenta mountain on the table with vocoder vocals and leads into some spacey sections. Before transitioning into Grim Reaper we get some seamless magma teases.
Featured Joey on Flute, an Aqualung (Jethro Tull) quote, and teases of Ants & Bats and Blindness (The Fall).
Beings with some light playful jamming that slowly becomes more driving and up-tempo before fully dropping into Hot Water.
Multiple sections of extensive jamming between verses, a bit of a Southern Rock flair, and a handful of teases.
A somewhat unique rendition in that the band goes into a seemingly non-microtonal jam directly in the middle of a microtonal song.
Evil Sense!
Contained nearly all of the lyrics to Torture Chamber, a bunch of new "Black Market Bargain" lyrics, and Beastie Boys/Limp Bizkit quotes.
A massive version of Garden Goblin that contains ambient improv interludes during both the start and end.

The song starts with a haunting ambient intro featuring Stu on electric flute. Eventually the familiar Shanghai melody comes fully in, and by the end of the song elements of Grow Wings and Fly are present, leading into a groovy section to cap off the longest rendition of Shanghai to date.
Energetic and jammy electronic rendition. Leads into a high tempo section with a driving beat, truly fitting the "Rave" moniker.
Extensive Land Before Timeland jam
Featuring opener Maddie Ashman on cello, this was an ambient jam leading into Set.
Electronic arrangement with some meandering and ambient sections as well as some heavier sections with lots of bass. Longest rendition to date.

This is the longest version of Kepler to date. Has an extended intro that sees Amby on Sax. The song has some really funky electronic jamming, some frenetic beats and high energy drums, and a section with robotic sounding melodies.
Once again featuring opener Maddie Ashman on cello, this was a more high energy jam that felt like an extended intro into The Silver Cord.
Second longest Wheel to date. Featured an extended intro and jamming throughout.
A longer than normal version containing a variety of teases, jamming, and an unusual soft section before the transition into Cellophane.
Particularly heavy jam, with throat singing from Stu and screaming from Amby.

Playful “Am I in Brisbane?” lyric changes and inspired jamming highlight this lengthy version. The band quietly build the song as they trickle teases in its calm intro before launching into the song proper. An extended section of mellow space unravels out of a dense, frenetic jam that sees some of the band’s freest playing all year before the song’s final verses kick off more high energy jamming with rapid-fire teases.

An ambient jam minus Cavs (bathroom break) starts off this Ice V which includes the intro of Panpsych. Cavs returns before they launch into the longest non-electronic rendition of the song yet, with plenty of teases.
